title: NSW GPs to diagnose and treat ADHD under landmark trial | 7NEWS
description: New South Wales is launching a landmark trial enabling 600 GPs to diagnose and treat ADHD in adults and children from March. The reforms will significantly reduce wait times of 3-12 months and costs of hundreds to thousands of dollars that patients currently face. The initiative is expected to particularly benefit patients in regional and rural areas who previously had limited access to ADHD diagnosis and treatment. title: Resident risks life fighting Enmore restaurant fire | 7NEWS
description: A fire broke out at a restaurant storage unit on Enmore Road, Newtown, at approximately 7:40pm, filling the street with smoke and drawing attention from nearby diners and concert-goers. A neighbouring resident, Paul Pickett, climbed out of his window with a fire extinguisher in an attempt to control the blaze before firefighters arrived and quickly extinguished it. No injuries were reported and the cause of the fire remains unknown, with no indication of suspicious circumstances at this stage. title: Exercise as effective as medication for depression | 7NEWS
description: New Australian research from James Cook University reveals that exercise is equally effective as medication and therapy for treating depression and anxiety. Aerobic activities like running, walking and swimming show significantly higher impact on depression symptoms, while group and supervised exercise also demonstrate strong benefits. The study found exercise particularly effective for postnatal depression, with researchers emphasising the importance of tailoring workout types to individual circumstances. title: Questions over alleged crime kingpin's Iraqi mugshot | 7NEWS
description: Alleged Melbourne tobacco wars kingpin Kazem Hamad is in Iraqi custody, but two mugshot images released by the Australian Federal Police have raised serious questions about their authenticity. One photo shows a height chart suggesting Hamad is 8 feet 9 inches tall, with apparent digital anomalies including distorted fingers and neckline. The AFP has not verified the images from Iraqi authorities, while Hamad's alleged crime syndicate faces internal conflict back in Melbourne, where his operation is linked to numerous tobacco store firebombings. title: Is the pub shout dying out in Australia? | 7NEWS
description: Australian pub culture is shifting as cost of living pressures change drinking habits. Payment provider Tyro's analysis of hundreds of millions of transactions reveals 32% of Australians are now less likely to buy rounds for their group, with half reporting changed drinking habits due to rising costs. Pubs are seeing increased use of QR code ordering, more bill splitting, and greater demand for food over drinks, with 19% of surveyed patrons reporting spending $100 on a single round.
